    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Pravum Cor hominis, et inscrutabile.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Jeremiah" book_title="Book of Jeremiah"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"The heart of men is perverse and unsearcheable."</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Policia[e] Ironia[e], pragmatic&egrave;, ueteratorieq[ue],
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Policia[e] Ironia[e]"/>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>dissimulata[e]; incredibile,
                    sa[e]pe effectus operantur.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Political ironies, having been disguised pragmatically and cunningly. Always they serve the preformance incredibly.</translation> <!--JG: Perhaps better: 'The effect of political ironies having been disquished cunningly and pragmatically: they always work'. What do you think, Chris?-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Tiberius Imp. aliud sempter pra[e]tendebat: aliud inte[n]debat.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tiberius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Emperor Tiberius always pretended one thing and intended another.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Socrates, Gra[e]coru[m], Sophistas, pla[e]ru[m]q[ue] laudabat [GREEK]. <!--JG: Chris, can you transcribe and translate the Greek-->
                        Solinus tradit, quasdam in terra Aphrica familias hominum, voce, linguaq[ue] effascinare:
                        qua[e] si impensi&ugrave;s fort&egrave;</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Socrates"/>
                    <person name="Solinus"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Socrates"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="laudabat"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="familias hominum"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="voce, linguaq[ue]"/>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>laudauerint pulchras Arbores; Segetes la[e]tiores; infantes ameniores;</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Egregios Equos;</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>pecudes pastu, atq[ue]</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>cultu opimas:</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>ea[e]dem derepent&egrave; emoriunt[u]r.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Scorates and many other Greeks praised the sofists [Greek term].<!--JG: Probably have to amend my translation. Would expect the Greek term to be the object here, don't really get why 'Sophistas' is in acc.-->
            Solinus related that in Africa certain families of men work spells by voice and tongue, who, if they would exceedingly and strongly praise beautiful trees,
            abounding crops, more pleasant children, and exceptional horses; by feeding sheep and by cultivating abundance: the same families would die out suddenly. </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Faber, bysshop of Vien,
                    gaue Simon Grineaus, Melanchtons Companion, fayer wordes of familiar conference, and gentle interteinement
                    [the] next day, in most curtuous manner: intending that uery night to make him fast, and pra[e]sently
                    dispatching Sergeants for his imprisonment,
                    by [the] kings commandiment:</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Johann Faber"/>
                    <person name="Simon Grynaeus"/>
                    <person name="Melanchton"/>
                    <location name="Vienna"/>
                    <X-ref person="John Foxe" book_title="Book of martyrs"/> <!--JG: Harvey seems to have paraphrased this from Foxe's 'Book of Martyrs' which contains a history of Simon Grinaeus.-->
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="fayer wordes"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="that uery night to make him fast"/>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>if Grineus had not immediatly pra[e]ventid his suttle praectise,
                    upon A suddain incling thereof, by an auncient owld man unknowen: who assurid him,
                    what woold be [the] end of Fabers goodly counterfayt glozinge.</marginalia_text> 
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Grineus had not immediatly"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>In malis uinci, malu[m] est.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Seneca" book_title="Phoenissae"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"To be defeated amidst bad things, is evil."</translation> <!--JG: There exist various variants (and hence translations) of this sentence-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Gabriel Haruey.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Gabriel Harvey"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Preciu[m] 2 [...] <!--JG: Unsure, seems as if two things have been written on top of each other-->
                    Mese Maio. 1578.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Price: 2 [...]. May, 1578.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
